Experiment 13

Aim: Write a trigger to demonstrate the use of Row level trigger and Statement level trigger.

Solution:
Statement-Level Trigger:
CREATE OR REPLACE TRIGGER trig_upt_student
BEFORE UPDATE ON student
BEGIN
    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('This is a statement-level trigger that got fired');
END;
/

Row-Level Trigger:
CREATE OR REPLACE TRIGGER trig_upt_student
BEFORE UPDATE ON student FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Row-level trigger got fired');
END;
/
Explanation:
•	Statement-Level Trigger:
o	The trig_upt_student trigger is a statement-level trigger that fires once before an UPDATE statement on the student table.
o	It displays a message when the trigger is activated.
•	Row-Level Trigger:
o	Another trig_upt_student trigger is a row-level trigger that fires before each row is updated in the student table.
o	It displays a message for each row that is affected by the UPDATE statement.
Outcome: This practical demonstrates the difference between row-level and statement-level triggers, teaching students how to use each type effectively.



